cture))) (Technology (Software (Intelligence AgentSystems)))] Clarification [The endpoint of the meta-work is the final software engine: an engine that self-improves to the point where nothing better could ever be made. The eventually-impossible-to-improve software of the workspace essence is reached through the engine improving itself, not only through human-directed refinement.] High High Zero [telos self-improving-engine])) (7c71 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Intelligence AgentSystems)))] Principle [|A programming language is in essence a set of structural macros — constructors taking a typed, counted set of objects (Rust's struct/enum/fn/impl/generics included). Conventional languages freeze that macro set in the compiler; this substrate treats it as data, so the language is infinitely extensible (constructs added as data, not compiler changes) and far easier for an LLM to read/write/reason about. Everything is data conforming to a schema type — a macro is a value of a struct whose pattern and template are ordinary typed fields; no privileged escape-hatch. A file's structure is a typed tree of structural-form nodes that recognise a block by shape and recursively decode children: the grammar is the type, the type is the reader, so no parser is hand-written (the aski elegant-syntax goal falls out of declaring typed nodes as data). The structural-macro-node grammar and NOTA's own grammar are schema-expressible, making the notation self-hosting; NOTA's delimiter set is a closed enum (three base pairs + three piped variants, two reserved as extension points). The next step is building that schema spec for the macro node.|] VeryHigh Medium Zero [schema-next nota-next aski macro-as-data])) (go9u ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Principle [LLM prompt and template prose lives in separate plain-text files, not embedded in Rust code; the code includes them at build time via include_str so the binary stays s